{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513934","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513934"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:16:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:16:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12252"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12252","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12252"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.15,0.81,0.02,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4774"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78441"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4774","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4774"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12252"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63803"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1111"},{"type":"tags","id":"1463"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"3090"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7612"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7642"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26765"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78441","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78441"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA family brings a 38-year-old patient against his will to the clinic. The family report he is very aggressive, throws things in his surroundings, physically abuses the staff at his job and has shown the same abusive behaviour at home for many years. When he was a child, he used to steal things, lie about small things and even used to hit his pet. His condition has worsened as he has grown up. He does not take care of his hygiene, violates laws and never shows guilt for any of his behaviour. He denies using psychoactive substances and has a negative urine drug screen.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Histrionic disorder","Conduct disorder","Antisocial personality disorder","Schizoid disorder","Obsessive compulsive disorder"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe age of the patient and his symptoms are suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003Eantisocial personality disorder (ASPD), \u003C/strong\u003Esometimes called sociopathy, is a mental disorder in which a person consistently shows no regard for right and wrong and ignores the rights and feelings of others. Individuals with antisocial personality disorder often violate the law, becoming criminals. They may lie, behave violently or impulsively, and have problems with drug and alcohol use. All individuals with ASPD have a history of conduct disorder in childhood.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConduct disorder \u003C/strong\u003Eon the other hand presents in childhood or early adolescence years. It presents with symptoms similar to ASPD i.e., aggressive, destructive, and deceitful behaviors and violating the rights of others. Not all conduct disordered children go on to develop ASPD but all adults with ASPD have evidence of childhood CD symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESchizoid personality disorder\u003C/strong\u003E is a condition in which people avoid social activities and consistently shy away from interaction with others. They also have a limited range of emotional expression. They prefer to be alone, not desiring relationships and show no emotions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObsessive compulsive disorder (OCD) \u003C/strong\u003Eis a common mental health condition where a person has obsessive thoughts and compulsive behaviors. An obsession is an unwanted and unpleasant thought, image or urge that repeatedly enters mind, causing feelings of anxiety, disgust or unease. A compulsion is a repetitive behavior in response to the obsession to temporarily relieve the unpleasant feelings brought on by the obsessive thought.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHistrionic personality disorder\u003C/strong\u003E, or commonly known as a dramatic personality disorder, is a psychiatric disorder distinguished by a pattern of exaggerated emotionality and attention-seeking behaviors. They become uncomfortable in situations where they are not the center of attention and often display inappropriate seductive or sexually provocative behaviors to seek attention.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Antisocial personality disorder (ASPD) is a mental disorder of adulthood in which a person shows aggressive, violent, impulsive and criminal behavior.","Individuals with antisocial personality disorder often have a history of conduct disorder in childhood."],"references":["Alcorn JL 3rd, Gowin JL, Green CE, Swann AC, Moeller FG, Lane SD. Aggression, impulsivity, and psychopathic traits in combined antisocial personality disorder and substance use disorder. J Neuropsychiatry Clin Neurosci. 2013 Summer;25(3):229-32. doi: 10.1176/appi.neuropsych.12030060. PMID: 24026715; PMCID: PMC4777890. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24026715/","Millon T (2000). Personality Disorders in Modern Life (Second ed.). Hoboken, New Jersey: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Inc. pp. 158\u2013161.","Fisher KA, Torrico TJ, Hany M. Antisocial Personality Disorder. 2024 Feb 29. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31536279. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31536279/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63803"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12252"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63803","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63803"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-10T18:50:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-10T18:51:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4774"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78441"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1111","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1111"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","nam